body:
I followed the build instructions as outlined here [https://github.com/Microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/master/BUILD.md](https://github.com/Microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/master/BUILD.md)

The one difference is that I added --x86 to target 32 bit (it's one of the Parameters documented in build.py) as my development machine is x64 and therefore the build process would otherwise have defaulted to an x64 build.

I hope this makes it a bit clearer what I did. Or is there one particular step you'd need more Information on?
Our list of officially released and supported packages doesn't include python x86. Your contributions are most welcome. Thanks!

Oh, I see - I mistakenly assumed that given that the base library supports x86-32 through the C-API it would be supported with Python bindings as well. I have a few more Questions:

1. Are there known technical issues with the x86-32 Python bindings or is it merely not covered by tests and therefore unsupported?
2. Might it be considered to support x86-32 Python officially in the future? If so - how could I help this along through contributions (I'd assume work would center around making sure the Python bindings against the C-API are unit tested, given that the core already supports x86-32).

Hi @OliverUlm , 
I got a similar message:

"/home/onnxruntimedev/Release/onnxruntime/capi/onnxruntime_validation.py:22: UserWarning: Unsupported architecture (32bit). ONNX Runtime supports 64bit architecture, only."

Is it the same thing you saw? But I guess it is just a warning. It won't block the execution.

> Oh, I see - I mistakenly assumed that given that the base library supports x86-32 through the C-API it would be supported with Python bindings as well. I have a few more Questions:
The python bindings don't use the C API interface. It statically links onnxruntime and uses the internal C++ API.

> 
> 1. Are there known technical issues with the x86-32 Python bindings or is it merely not covered by tests and therefore unsupported?
We've never tried building since we don't have any requirements.

> 2. Might it be considered to support x86-32 Python officially in the future? If so - how could I help this along through contributions (I'd assume work would center around making sure the Python bindings against the C-API are unit tested, given that the core already supports x86-32).
We don't have any such requirements, but you're most welcome to contribute. However we won't be releasing official packages.

There may be additional pybind11 flags needed for the shared object to compile properly on 32-bit architecture. I had to similarly fiddle with the build script when building onnxruntime for Python 2.7 (see here: https://github.com/akavalar/onnxruntime & especially the list of tweaks needed here: https://github.com/Microsoft/onnxruntime/compare/master...akavalar:master), and in the end I got it to work flawlessly.

It does seem what you've described is just a warning as pointed out by @snnn though.
Unsurprisingly, this warning also pops up when importing on ARM build (Raspberry Pi).

@OliverUlm would you like to contribute towards fixing the warning message? As I said before, currently, we don't have any plans to support python wheels for x86 arch, but you're more than welcome to contribute. The python bindings use the internal C++ API, not the C API.
